I"‰<p>By far, the biggest bit of feedback I‚Äôve gotten on <a href="/2006/02/showing-perfect-time-unobtrusively">‚ÄúShowing Perfect Time‚Äù</a> is the glaringly invalid attribute (<code class="highlighter-rouge">gmt_time</code>) in the structure I chose to use (from <a href="http://ecmanaut.blogspot.com/2006/01/ajax-date-time-time-zones-best.html#c113978133722812093">Johan Sundstr√∂m</a>, for example).  I don‚Äôt think that the attribute by itself is a huge deal, and <a href="http://www.quirksmode.org/">Peter-Paul Koch</a> makes <a href="http://alistapart.com/articles/scripttriggers/" title="JavaScript Triggers">a convincing argument</a> for that position at <a href="http://alistapart.com/">A List Apart</a>.</p>

<p>However, <a href="http://ifstatement.blogspot.com/">Daniel Morrison</a> points out that the display of dates on webpages is already more or less a solved problem.  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/hcalendar#Example">hCalendar</a> is a <a href="http://microformats.org/">microformat</a> used by blogs all over the place to display dates and times, and there‚Äôs absolutely no good reason why I should try to invent a new format rather than using one already in the wild.</p>

<p>I‚Äôve rewritten <a href="/projects/files/PerfectTime/PerfectTime.js">PerfectTime.js</a> to support the <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/hcalendar#Example">hCalendar</a> format (<a href="/projects/files/PerfectTime/PerfectTimeDemo.php">an updated PHP-driven demo</a> is also avaliable), and I‚Äôll describe the changes in the remainder of this article.</p>

<p>The <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/hcalendar#Example">hCalendar</a> format uses an <code class="highlighter-rouge">abbr</code> tag to display dates and times.  The date is machine-readable in the tag‚Äôs <code class="highlighter-rouge">title</code> attribute, while the element‚Äôs contents are human-readable.  For example:</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;abbr title="2005-10-08"&gt;October 8th, 2005&lt;/abbr&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Or, for slightly more complexity:</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;abbr title="19721128T115524-0800"&gt;Tue, 28 Nov 1972 11:55:24 -0800&lt;/abbr&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The <code class="highlighter-rouge">title</code> attribute is encoded according to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601">ISO 8601</a>, while the human readable contents can be formatted however you like.  I‚Äôve modified the original PerfectTime class to support this format, with the following caveats:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>The script only attempts to modify <code class="highlighter-rouge">abbr</code> elements of class <code class="highlighter-rouge">PerfectTime</code>.
If you want your beginning and ending <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/hcalendar#Example">hCalendar</a> times to be localized,
you‚Äôll have to set them as something like:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;abbr class='dtend *PerfectTime*' title='...'&gt;...&lt;/abbr&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>ISO 8601 is not completely supported.  Specifically, the formats accepted 
by this script are the following:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>YYYY
YYYY-MM
YYYY-MM-DD
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM[+-]HHMM
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.sZ
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.s
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.s[+-]HHMM    
YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.sZ
</code></pre></div>    </div>

    <p>Additionally, the hyphens seperating the date components and the colons
seperating the time components are optional.  For example, ‚ÄúMarch 22, 2006 
at 12:00 CET (+0100)‚Äù could be written as any of:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>2006-03-22T12:00+0100        
20060322T12:00+0100        
2006-03-22T1100Z
</code></pre></div>    </div>

    <p>All of those point to the exact same minute in time.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The script does not (yet) support the ‚Äòweek dates‚Äô (YYYY-Www-D) or ‚Äòordinal
dates‚Äô (YYYY-DDD) formats.  This probably won‚Äôt be a problem for most usages
since my impression is that a script like this will likely be used for hours
and minutes much more than for specific days.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>The piece of the script that parses <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601">ISO 8601</a> timestamps is based on <a href="http://delete.me.uk/2005/03/iso8601.html">Paul Sowden‚Äôs parser</a>.  I‚Äôve modified it to fit into the self-contained JavaScript class we‚Äôre looking at here, to make the colons and hyphens optional, and to reuse a single <code class="highlighter-rouge">RegEx</code> object instead of creating a new one on every parse.</p>

<p>To verify that the methods are giving the same times, I modified the <a href="/projects/files/PerfectTime/PerfectTimeDemo.php">the PerfectTime demo page</a> to generate 10 random timestamps between 1970 and 2010, and output both the <code class="highlighter-rouge">span</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">abbr</code> formats.  It looks like it‚Äôs working pretty well for me on Firefox, but I don‚Äôt have access to a windows machine right now, so I‚Äôve no idea if it‚Äôs working correctly there.  I‚Äôd love it if someone would bang on that for me and let me know how it goes.</p>

<p>With that said, <a href="/projects/files/PerfectTime/PerfectTime.js">PerfectTime 1.1</a> is ready for you to run away with.</p>
